CYBV311 - Hello World (Linux / x86-64 NASM)
===========================================

This is the Linux counterpart to the Windows program in HelloWorldASM. It is a
small "Hello World" written in x86-64 assembly for the NASM assembler that calls
the C runtime printf function to print a greeting, then returns to libc, which
exits the process.

Use it to validate a Linux install: if it assembles, links, and runs, then the
NASM assembler, the GNU linker (ld), and the C runtime (libc) are all present
and working on the machine.

Unlike the 32-bit Windows version, this program follows the System V AMD64
calling convention (first argument in RDI, AL = number of vector registers for
variadic calls) and has no leading-underscore name decoration, so the entry
point is 'main' and it calls 'printf' directly.


Requirements
------------

  * nasm  - the NASM assembler
  * gcc   - the GNU C compiler / linker (pulls in libc for printf)
  * ld    - the GNU linker (installed alongside gcc)

On Debian or Ubuntu:

  sudo apt install nasm gcc gdb

On Fedora or RHEL:

  sudo dnf install nasm gcc gdb

(gdb is only needed for debugging - see the Debugging section below.)


Build and run
-------------

The included Makefile does everything:

  make        # assemble and link -> ./hello
  make run    # build (if needed) and run it
  make clean  # remove the generated hello.o and hello

Or run the steps by hand:

  nasm -f elf64 hello.asm -o hello.o
  gcc -no-pie hello.o -o hello
  ./hello

Expected output:

  Welcome to CYBV311!!


Debugging
---------

To step through the program you must build with debug symbols. NASM needs the
-g option (and -F dwarf to select the DWARF format that gdb reads); gcc needs
-g as well. The Makefile's "debug" target does both:

  make debug     # nasm -f elf64 -g -F dwarf ... ; gcc -no-pie -g ...
  make gdb       # build with symbols, then launch gdb on ./hello

You can confirm the symbols landed with:

  readelf -S hello | grep debug

If you see sections like .debug_info and .debug_line, gdb can show source
lines.


Debugging with gdb (command line)
.................................

  make gdb              # or: make debug && gdb ./hello

  (gdb) break main      # stop at our entry point
  (gdb) run             # start; halts at main
  (gdb) layout regs     # TUI: source + live registers (recommended for asm)
  (gdb) stepi           # execute one instruction (repeat to step along)
  (gdb) nexti           # like stepi, but step OVER "call printf"
  (gdb) info registers  # dump all registers
  (gdb) x/s $rdi        # show the string RDI points to (the format arg)
  (gdb) continue        # run to completion -> prints the greeting
  (gdb) quit


Debugging in VS Code (WSL)
..........................

Config files live in .vscode/launch.json and .vscode/tasks.json.

  1. From a WSL shell in this folder, run:  code .
     This reopens VS Code connected to WSL with this folder as the workspace.
  2. Install the "WSL" extension (ms-vscode-remote.remote-wsl) and the
     "C/C++" extension (ms-vscode.cpptools). The C/C++ extension must be
     installed in the WSL remote (use "Install in WSL"), not just on Windows.
  3. Open hello.asm and click the gutter to set a breakpoint.
  4. Press F5. VS Code runs "make debug" first (the preLaunchTask) so the
     binary has symbols, then launches it under gdb and stops at entry.

     F10 = step over, F11 = step into (one instruction), F5 = continue,
     Shift+F5 = stop. Expand VARIABLES -> Registers -> CPU to watch rdi/rax.
     Right-click in the editor -> "Open Disassembly View" to step by
     instruction alongside the source.



